Task 4: Dockerize a Web Application

Objective: Create a simple HTML web application, write a Dockerfile, build an image, and run the container mapping port 80 to 8080.

1. Setup & Installation

If Docker is not installed, install it first:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install docker.io -y
sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl enable docker


2. Create Project Directory & Files

Create Directory:

mkdir appDocker
cd appDocker


Create index.html:

gedit index.html


Content:

<h1>Hello From Docker</h1>


Create Dockerfile:
Note: The filename must be exactly Dockerfile (Capital 'D').

gedit Dockerfile


Content:

# Use Nginx as the base image
FROM nginx:latest

# Copy local index.html to the Nginx html directory
COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/


3. Build the Docker Image

Run the build command. The -t flag tags the image with a name and version.

# Syntax: sudo docker build -t <image-name>:<tag> .
sudo docker build -t html-app:1.0 .


Note: The . at the end specifies the current directory as the build context.

4. Run the Container

Run the container in detached mode (-d) and map port 8080 on the host to port 80 in the container (-p).

# Syntax: sudo docker run -d -p <host-port>:<container-port> <image-name>:<tag>
sudo docker run -d -p 8080:80 html-app:1.0


5. Verify

Open your web browser and go to http://localhost:8080. You should see "Hello From Docker".

Task 5: Docker Operations

Objective: Perform standard Docker operations: listing, stopping, and removing containers and images.

1. List Images and Containers

List all images:

sudo docker images


List running containers:

sudo docker ps


List all containers (running and stopped):

sudo docker ps -a


2. Stop a Container

Find the CONTAINER ID from the docker ps command and use it to stop the container.

sudo docker stop <CONTAINER_ID>


3. Remove a Container

Once stopped, you can remove the container to free up space/names.

sudo docker rm <CONTAINER_ID>


4. Remove an Image

To delete the image we built:

# Syntax: sudo docker rmi <image-name>:<tag>
sudo docker rmi html-app:1.0
